{"cursor":"2556","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"The 'Allon Plan' () was a proposal to end the Israeli occupation of the West\nBank with a negotiated partition of the territory between Israel and the\nHashemite Kingdom of Jordan. It is named after Yigal Allon, who drafted it\nshortly after the Six-Day War in June 1967.\n\n\nThe broad aim of the plan was to annex most of the Jordan Valley from the river\nto the eastern slopes of the West Bank hill ridge, East Jerusalem, and the\nEtzion bloc to Israel. At the same time, the heavily populated areas of the West\nBank hill country, together with a corridor that included Jericho, would be\noffered to Jordan. Ian S. Lustick,\n[http://www.sas.upenn.edu/penncip/lustick/lustick13.html For the land and the\nLord: Jewish fundamentalism in Israel], chapter 3, par. Early Activities of Gush\nEmunim. 1988, the Council on Foreign Relations\n\nThe Plan was shown to King Hussein, who rejected it, saying \"My problem is how\nto explain the solution to my nation if it is not a solution that will be\nacceptable to the Arab awareness.\" Reuven Pedatzur, [http://www.haaretz.com/print-edition/features/the-jordanian-option-the-plan-\nthat-refuses-to-die-1.226164 The 'Jordanian option,' the plan that refuses to\ndie]. Haaretz, 25 July 2007\n\nThe plan also included the creation of a Druze state in Syria's Quneitra\nGovernorate, including the Israeli-held Golan Heights. Akiva Eldar,\n[http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/988828.html A matter of a few dozen\nmeters]. Haaretz, 1 June 2008 Allon died in 1980, and the following year\nthe Israeli government passed the Golan Heights Law, effectively annexing most\nof the governorate.\n\nThe plan had many similarities with the Elon Peace Plan (\"the Jordan option\").\n","linknr":183,"url":"Allon_Plan","recorded":1375077638,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Allon_Plan&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Allon_Plan&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.